{"type":"message","id":"8e0af13b","parentId":"b4837304","timestamp":"2026-03-13T22:10:16.499Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have enough info to give a thorough answer.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Got it all. Here's the breakdown:\n\n---\n\n## What It Is\n\n**Qwen3.5-27B-Claude-4.6-Opus-Reasoning-Distilled** is a 27B parameter reasoning model made by taking Alibaba's **Qwen3.5-27B** base and fine-tuning it (SFT + LoRA) on **Claude 4.6 Opus reasoning chains** — essentially teaching a smaller, open model to think like Claude Opus.\n\nThe training data is ~3,200+ filtered Claude Opus reasoning trajectories (from datasets `nohurry/Opus-4.6-Reasoning-3000x-filtered` and others). The key idea: distill Opus's structured, step-by-step Chain-of-Thought into a model that can run locally.\n\n### What makes it notable:\n\n1. **Native \"developer\" role support** — works out of the box with Claude Code, OpenCode, and other coding agents that use the `developer` message role (the base Qwen model crashes on this due to Jinja template issues)\n2. **Thinking mode preserved** — full `<think>...</think>` chain-of-thought, not silently stripped\n3. **9+ minutes autonomous coding agent runs** — doesn't stall mid-execution like the base model\n4. **262K context window** intact\n5. **Apache 2.0 license** — fully permissive\n\n### Community benchmarks (single RTX 3090):\n- ~**16.5 GB VRAM** with Q4_K_M quantization\n- **29–35 tok/s** generation speed\n\n---\n\n## How to Deploy Locally\n\n### Option 1: llama.cpp / Ollama (easiest for consumer hardware)\n\nThe model page has quantized GGUF versions already available. There are 17 quantized variants on HuggingFace:\n\n```bash\n# With Ollama (if a community quant exists):\nollama run hf.co/Jackrong/Qwen3.5-27B-Claude-4.6-Opus-Reasoning-Distilled\n\n# Or download a GGUF manually and use llama.cpp:\n# Q4_K_M fits in ~16.5 GB VRAM — good for a single RTX 3090 / 24GB card\n```\n\n### Option 2: vLLM (for multi-GPU or server deployment)\n\n```bash\npip install vllm\n\nvllm serve Jackrong/Qwen3.5-27B-Claude-4.6-Opus-Reasoning-Distilled \\\n  --dtype bfloat16 \\\n  --max-model-len 262144\n```\n\nThe full BF16 model is ~56 GB across 11 safetensors shards, so you'd need 2x A100 80GB or similar for unquantized. For single-GPU, use AWQ/GPTQ quantization.\n\n### Option 3: Transformers + Unsloth (for fine-tuning or custom inference)\n\n```bash\npip install unsloth transformers torch\n\nfrom unsloth import FastLanguageModel\n\nmodel, tokenizer = FastLanguageModel.from_pretrained(\n    \"Jackrong/Qwen3.5-27B-Claude-4.6-Opus-Reasoning-Distilled\",\n    max_seq_length=262144,\n    dtype=torch.bfloat16,\n    load_in_4bit=True,  # Q4 — fits in ~16 GB VRAM\n)\n```\n\n### Option 4: LM Studio / Jan (GUI-based)\n\nBoth are listed as supported apps. Download the quantized GGUF, load in LM Studio, done.\n\n---\n\n### TL;DR\n\nThis is essentially a **local Claude Opus reasoning clone** built on Qwen3.5-27B. If you've got 16+ GB VRAM and want a model that thinks in structured CoT and plays nice with coding agents, this is one of the more interesting community distills out there. The `developer` role fix alone makes it worth using over the base Qwen3.5-27B for agentic workflows."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/hunter-alpha","usage":{"input":21212,"output":923,"cacheRead":39424,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":61559,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773439798672}}
{"type":"message","id":"5aa497bc","parentId":"8e0af13b","timestamp":"2026-03-13T22:24:12.988Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sat 2026-03-14 06:24 GMT+8] can the model be run on a Mac Studio with 64GB or 128GB RAM? also is browsing with agent-browser behaving as expected? any issue or hiccup in using agent-browser? what is your experience with agent-browser?"}],"timestamp":1773440652982}}
{"type":"message","id":"dcfe75d8","parentId":"5aa497bc","timestamp":"2026-03-13T22:24:31.603Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking two things:\n1. Can the model run on a Mac Studio with 64GB or 128GB RAM?\n2. How was my experience with agent-browser?\n\nLet me answer both thoroughly.\n\nFor the Mac Studio question - yes, absolutely. The full BF16 model is ~56GB, and with quantization it's much smaller. Mac Studios with Apple Silicon have unified memory, so you can use the full RAM for model inference via llama.cpp with Metal.\n\nFor agent-browser - let me reflect on my experience. I had the version mismatch issue (chromium-1208 vs chromium_headless_shell-1200) which required using `--executable-path`. That's worth noting honestly.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"## Mac Studio: Absolutely yes.\n\nThe full unquantized BF16 model is ~56 GB across 11 shards. Here's how it breaks down:\n\n**64 GB Mac Studio:**\n- Full BF16: tight but doable — ~56 GB model + OS overhead = cutting it close\n- **Q4_K_M quant (~16 GB):** runs comfortably, lots of headroom for long context\n- **Q5_K_M or Q6_K (~20–24 GB):** sweet spot for quality/VRAM tradeoff on 64 GB\n\n**128 GB Mac Studio:**\n- Full BF16: runs easily, room for 262K context\n- You could even run it alongside other models or a large context window with zero stress\n\n**How to run it** — llama.cpp is the way to go on Apple Silicon (Metal backend):\n```bash\n# Download a GGUF quant from the HuggingFace repo\n# Then:\n./llama-server -m Qwen3.5-27B-Claude-4.6-Opus-Q4_K_M.gguf \\\n  --ctx-size 32768 \\\n  -ngl 99  # offload all layers to Metal\n```\n\nMLX (Apple's native framework) is another option if there's an MLX conversion available, but llama.cpp + GGUF quants are more readily available for this model. LM Studio also works great on Mac if you want a GUI.\n\n**Expected speed:** roughly 15–30 tok/s on M2 Ultra depending on quant level and context length. Not Opus-speed, but very usable for coding agent workflows.\n\n---\n\n## agent-browser: Honest Review\n\nIt works, but there was a real hiccup:\n\n**The problem:** There's a Playwright version mismatch. agent-browser bundles code expecting `chromium_headless_shell-1200`, but what actually installed is `chromium-1208` and `chromium_headless_shell-1208`. This means the default launch fails with:\n\n```\nExecutable doesn't exist at .../chromium_headless_shell-1200/...\n```\n\n**The workaround:** I had to pass `--executable-path /home/pete/.cache/ms-playwright/chromium-1208/chrome-linux64/chrome` and close/reopen the daemon between runs. That's annoying for quick usage.\n\n**What worked well once running:**\n- `snapshot -i` — excellent. Clean accessibility tree with deterministic `@e1`, `@e2` refs. Much better than guessing CSS selectors.\n- `screenshot` — just works.\n- `open <url>` — fast, reliable navigation.\n- Daemon architecture is nice — commands after the first are snappy.\n\n**Bottom line:** The tool itself is well-designed (the ref-based interaction model is genuinely smart for AI usage), but the Chromium version mismatch on this machine is a friction point. If you plan to use it regularly, either pin a compatible Playwright version or set up an alias with `--executable-path`. I'd still reach for it over raw Playwright scripts when doing quick page inspections — the snapshot-ref workflow is faster to reason about."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/hunter-alpha","usage":{"input":4083,"output":996,"cacheRead":57600,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":62679,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773440652984}}
